  "prompt": "Who investigates the Federal Bureau of Investigation?",
  "response": "The Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) is primarily overseen and investigated by several entities to ensure accountability and transparency. These include:\n\n1. **Department of Justice (DOJ)**: The FBI operates under the DOJ, and the Attorney General, who heads the DOJ, has oversight responsibilities.\n\n2. **Office of the Inspector General (OIG) within the DOJ**: This independent entity conducts audits, investigations, and reviews to detect and prevent misconduct and waste within the FBI and other components of the DOJ.\n\n3. **Congress**: Through committees such as the House Judiciary Committee and the Senate Judiciary Committee, Congress conducts oversight of the FBI, holding hearings and investigations to scrutinize its operations and policies.\n\n4. **Government Accountability Office (GAO)**: As a legislative branch agency, the GAO conducts audits and evaluations of government programs, including those managed by the FBI, to ensure they are operating efficiently and effectively.\n\nThese entities work together to ensure that the FBI maintains its integrity and operates within the bounds of the law.",
